  "family": "Wolff-Kishner Reduction",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "O=C(C)CC"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "CCCC"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "NN",
      "[OH-].[K+]"
    ],
    "rationale": "This reaction shows the reduction of a simple, acyclic ketone (butan-2-one) to the corresponding alkane (n-butane) using hydrazine (NN) and potassium hydroxide ([OH-].[K+]), which are the classic reagents for the Wolff-Kishner reduction. The transformation is a clear deoxygenation of a carbonyl group to a methylene group, which is the defining feature of this reaction. The substrates and products are small, acyclic, and lack complex functional groups, making this a canonical and unambiguous example.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple aliphatic ketone to avoid overlap with reactions involving aromatic systems (e.g., Friedel-Crafts acylation followed by reduction) or other functional groups that might be sensitive to the strongly basic conditions. It is distinct from the Clemmensen reduction, which achieves the same transformation under acidic conditions. The simplicity of the substrate ensures it is a specific example of the Wolff-Kishner reduction and not a more general deoxygenation reaction."
  }
}
